            {"title":"Pre vs Post Increment","code":"#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main() {\n    int x = 10;\n    printf(\"x   = %d\\n\", x);     // 10\n    printf(\"x++ = %d\\n\", x++);   // 10 (use, then increment)\n    printf(\"x   = %d\\n\", x);     // 11\n    printf(\"++x = %d\\n\", ++x);   // 12 (increment, then use)\n    return 0;\n}","output":"x   = 10\nx++ = 10\nx   = 11\n++x = 12","explanation":"<p>Post-increment returns the current value then increments; pre-increment increments first. This distinction matters in loop conditions and expressions.</p>"},
